description: Latin proceleusmaticus, from Ancient Greek προκελευσματικὸς (prokeleusmatikòs), to rouse to action beforehand, to incite.

adjectives.description: proceleusmatic (comparative more proceleusmatic, superlative most proceleusmatic)

examples: The ancient proceleusmatic song , by which the rowers of gallies were animated , may be supposed to have been of this kind

entries.meaning: (poetry, not comparable) Consisting of four short syllables; composed of metrical feet of four short syllables each.
(poetry) A metrical foot consisting of four short syllables.
